result.execSummary:
The defendant Jhamar D James was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Carry Concealed Weapon, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 941.23(2).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Request for Huber / Work Release Modification received from HOC and filed this date.  This case is assigned and forwarded to JudgeSiefert, Br 47 for review. os

Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the State, defense and defendant.  Additional statements by: David James Sr.  

As to Count 1:
The Court ordered defendant to serve 6 months in the House of Correction, consecutive to any other sentence, with credit for 1 day time served.  The Court granted Huber privileges, pursuant to 303.08 Wis. Stats. for work ONLY.

Court ordered defendant to provide a DNA sample and pay the DNA surcharge.

Court ordered defendant to pay all applicable court costs, fees and surcharges (including DNA surcharge) by 11/21/2019, or serve 15 days in the House of Correction.

Defendant to report by 11/25/2016 by 5:00 p.m.

Defendant Jhamar D James in court with attorney Mark Allan Dluzak.  Kelly O'Neill appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  

As to Count 1:
Defendant changes his plea to GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to his plea, advised of his Constitutional rights and the maximum penalty.   Defendant advised that if not a United States Citizen, deportation is possible.  Court found that defendant knowingly, voluntarily and intelligently waived his rights.  Guilty Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights and Addendum received and filed.  Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea.  Court found defendant guilty and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record.  

As to Count 2:
Pursuant to plea negotiations and on motion of the State, Court ordered Count 2 dismissed and read-in to case for the purposes of sentencing.
